<div class="alert alert-info mb-4" role="alert">
    <h4 class="alert-heading"><span class="bi bi-info-circle"></span> About These Samples</h4>
    <p>
        This page demonstrates three different approaches to implementing button click handlers in Blazor, 
        each shown in both synchronous and asynchronous versions:
    </p>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-4">
            <h6><span class="bi bi-1-circle"></span> Traditional Approach</h6>
            <p class="small">
                <strong>ExistingExample / ExistingExampleAsync:</strong> 
                Standard Blazor button with <code>@@onclick</code> event handler. Requires manual state management for loading states and button disabling.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4">
            <h6><span class="bi bi-2-circle"></span> Button + RelayCommand</h6>
            <p class="small">
                <strong>Example1 / Example1Async:</strong> 
                Regular <code>&lt;button&gt;</code> element bound to a ViewModel's <code>RelayCommand</code>. Provides automatic state management through the command pattern.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4">
            <h6><span class="bi bi-3-circle"></span> MvvmButton Component</h6>
            <p class="small">
                <strong>Example2 / Example2Async:</strong> 
                Custom <code>&lt;MvvmButton&gt;</code> component that automatically binds to ViewModel commands with built-in loading states and disabled state management.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <p class="mb-0">
        <span class="bi bi-lightbulb"></span> <strong>Key Benefit:</strong> 
        The MvvmButton approach provides the cleanest markup and automatic handling of command states, loading indicators, and concurrency control.
    </p>
</div>